result.execSummary:
Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: From April 6, 2016 before Honorable Steven P Anderson,  Plea hearing for 14CF49, Init App for 15CF49 all encompassed in hearing, prepared by court reporter Shannon Golat

Filed in 14CF49.  It is Ordered that Justin Siiter is released from the RC Jail to attend the victim/impact panel at the LHS on June 2, 2015 from 5:30PM until the conclusion on the meeting, which is approximately 7:30PM.  Justin Siiter shall return to the RC Jail immediately after the meeting.

Defendant Justin A Siiter in court with attorney Erika Caroline Bahnson.  James Jay Rennicke appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Heard along with 14CF49.  Agreement has been reached in both cases.  Court recites case settlement into the court record.  Court instructs on plea questionnaire/waiver of rights.  
 14CF49- Withhold sentence, 3 yrs probation, will serve 60 days jail, with huber.  Has credit for 46 days.  Modifiers will be dismissed.  
15CF59 will be dismissed but read in.
DE will enter a plea of NC to 14CF49, Ct 1.  Court will accept and find the DE guilty.  Court instructs on preparation of PSI, DE will waive PSI preparation.  
Court will accept the recommendations of the parties.  DE reads a letter of apology to the court.  If DE is accepted to drug court, DE MUST complete Drug court.  DE must maintain absolute sobriety, no alcohol possession or consumption, do not enter premises where alcohol is the primary business, no possession of drugs without a valid prescription, will have credit for time served, will pay CC, will have Huber privilege.
